15/09/2021, 22:52 - Sandeepti Singh: // lab 2 comp 2011
// https://magisterrex.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/mastermindrules.pdf
// Cindy https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dMHxyulGrEk

#include <iostream> 
#include <cstdlib>
#include <time.h>  
using namespace std;

int main() 
{
    srand( time(NULL) );
    //Codemaker's choice of a random 4-color combination among six colors 
    // 1 Yellow, 2 Orange, 3 black, 4 Green, 5 Blue, 6 Purple
    int p0 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p1 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p2 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p3 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6

    // variable for code breaker's guess
    int g0;
    int g1;
    int g2;
    int g3;

    // variable for codemaker's response
    // red: correct color and correct position
    // white: correct color but wrong position
    // red overrides white
    int redpin;
    int whitepin;

    //you may declare additional variables here  to help you solve the problem:
    
    int attemptNumber = 1 ;  






    
    bool debug = true;

    cout << "==============================" << endl;
    cout << "Welcome to the Mastermind Game" << endl;
    cout << "==============================" << endl;

    if (debug){
        cout << "Coder maker's colors:" << endl;
        cout << "p0=" << p0 << "\tp1=" << p1 << "\tp2=" << p2 << "\tp3=" << p3 << endl << endl;
    }

    cout << "Code maker has made his choice." << endl;
    cout << "Code breaker, you have 12 attempts to crack his code." << endl;
    cout << "Game starts!" << endl << endl;

    
    // Write your code below this section:
    do {
    cout << "Attempt " << attemptNumber << endl; 
    cout <<"Please input your guess for the four positions: "<< endl; 
    cout << "Position 1: ";
    cin >> g0; 
    cout << "Position 2: ";
    cin >> g1; 
    cout << "Position 3: ";
    cin >> g2; 
    cout << "Position 4: ";
    cin >> g3; 

    redpin = 0; 
    whitepin = 0; 
    //Calculating red pins; 
    if(p0 == g0){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p1 == g1){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p2 == g2){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p3 == g3){
        redpin += 1;
    }


    if (g0 == p0 || g0 == p1 || g0 == p2 || g0 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1;
        if (g0 == p0){
            whitepin-= 1;
        }
        if (g0 == g1 && g1 == p1){ 
            whitepin-=1; 
        } 
            if (g0 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
            whitepin-=1; 
        } 
            if (g0 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
            whitepin-=1; 
        } 
        
    }


    if (g1 == p0 || g1 == p1 || g1 == p2 || g1 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1; 
        if (g1 == p1){
            whitepin -=1;
        } 
        if (g1 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
        whitepin-=1; 
        }
        if (g1 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
        whitepin-=1; 
        }
        if (g1 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
        whitepin-=1; 
        } 
    }





    if (g2 == p0 || g2 == p1 || g2 == p2 || g2 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1; 
        if (g2 == p2){
            whitepin -=1;
        }
        if (g2 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
        whitepin-=1; 
        }
        if (g2 == g1 && g1== p1){ 
        whitepin-=1; 
        }
        if (g2 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
        whitepin-=1; 
         } 
    }  



    
    

        if (g3 == p0 || g3 == p1 || g3 == p2 || g3 == p3){
            whitepin+= 1; 
            if (g3 == g3){
                whitepin -= 1;
            } 
            if (g3 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
            whitepin-=1; 
            } 
            if (g3 == g1 && g1 == p1){ 
            whitepin-=1; 
            } 
            if (g3 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
            whitepin-=1; 
            } 
        }

    if (whitepin < 0){
        whitepin = 0; 
    }

    cout<< "Red pins: " << redpin << "     White pins: " << whitepin << endl;  
    if (redpin == 4){
        cout << "Congratulations!" << endl;
        cout << "Code maker's colors: " << endl; 
        cout << "p0=" << p0 << "     p1=" <<p1 << "     p2=" << p2 << "     p3="<< p3 << endl; 
        cout << "You cracked the code with " << attemptNumber << " attempt(s)" ; 
        break; 
    }

    attemptNumber += 1;



    } while (attemptNumber < 12); 







    // Player runs out of attempts and loses 
    if (attemptNumber > 11){
    cout << "Sorry, you ran out of turns :( "<< endl; 
    }

    return 0;
}

int main() 
{

    int p0 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6

#include <iostream> 
#include <cstdlib>
#include <time.h>  
using namespace std;

int main() 
{
    srand( time(NULL) );
    //Codemaker's choice of a random 4-color combination among six colors 
    // 1 Yellow, 2 Orange, 3 black, 4 Green, 5 Blue, 6 Purple
    int p0 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p1 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p2 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p3 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6

    // variable for code breaker's guess
    int g0;
    int g1;
    int g2;
    int g3;

    // variable for codemaker's response
    // red: correct color and correct position
    // white: correct color but wrong position
    // red overrides white
    int redpin;
    int whitepin;

    //you may declare additional variables here  to help you solve the problem:
    
    int attemptNumber = 1 ;  






    
    bool debug = true;

    cout << "==============================" << endl;
    cout << "Welcome to the Mastermind Game" << endl;
    cout << "==============================" << endl;

    if (debug){
        cout << "Coder maker's colors:" << endl;
        cout << "p0=" << p0 << "\tp1=" << p1 << "\tp2=" << p2 << "\tp3=" << p3 << endl << endl;
    }

    cout << "Code maker has made his choice." << endl;
    cout << "Code breaker, you have 12 attempts to crack his code." << endl;
    cout << "Game starts!" << endl << endl;

    
    // Write your code below this section:
    do {
    cout << "Attempt " << attemptNumber << endl; 
    cout <<"Please input your guess for the four positions: "<< endl; 
    //cout << "Position 1: ";
    cin >> g0; 
    //cout << "Position 2: ";
    cin >> g1; 
    //cout << "Position 3: ";
    cin >> g2; 
   // cout << "Position 4: ";
    cin >> g3; 

    redpin = 0; 
    whitepin = 0; 
    //Calculating red pins; 
    if(p0 == g0){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p1 == g1){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p2 == g2){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p3 == g3){
        redpin += 1;
    }


    if (g0 == p1 || g0 == p2 || g0 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1;
    }
    if (g0 == g1 && g1 == p1){ 
        --whitepin; 
    } 
        if (g0 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
        --whitepin; 
    } 
        if (g0 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
        --whitepin; 
    }     


    if (g1 == p0 || g1 == p2 || g1 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1;
    }
    if (g1 == g0 && g0 == p0){

    --whitepin; 
    }
    if (g1 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
    --whitepin; 
    }

        whitepin+= 1; 
    }
    if (g2 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
    --whitepin; 
    }
    if (g2 == g1 && g1== p1){ 
    --whitepin; 
    }
    if (g2 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
    --whitepin; 
        } 
    



    
    

    if (g3 == p0 || g3 == p1 || g3 == p2){
        whitepin+= 1;
    }
    if (g3 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 
    if (g3 == g1 && g1 == p1){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 
    if (g3 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 


    if (whitepin < 0){
        whitepin = 0; 
    }

    cout<< "Red pins: " << redpin << "     White pins: " << whitepin << endl;  
    if (redpin == 4){
        cout << "Congratulations!" << endl;
        cout << "Code maker's colors: " << endl; 
        cout << "p0=" << p0 << "     p1=" <<p1 << "     p2=" << p2 << "     p3="<< p3 << endl; 
        cout << "You cracked the code with " << attemptNumber << " attempt(s)" ; 
        break; 
    }

    attemptNumber += 1;



    } while (attemptNumber < 13); 







    // Player runs out of attempts and loses 
    if (attemptNumber > 12){
    cout << "Sorry, you ran out of turns :( "<< endl; 
    }

    return 0;
}

18/09/2021, 11:35 - Sandeepti Singh: // lab 2 comp 2011
// https://magisterrex.files.wordpress.com/2014/07/mastermindrules.pdf
// Cindy https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dMHxyulGrEk

#include <iostream> 
#include <cstdlib>
#include <time.h>  
using namespace std;

int main() 
{
    srand( time(NULL) );
    //Codemaker's choice of a random 4-color combination among six colors 
    // 1 Yellow, 2 Orange, 3 black, 4 Green, 5 Blue, 6 Purple
    int p0 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p1 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p2 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6
    int p3 = rand() % 6 + 1; // 1 to 6

    // variable for code breaker's guess
    int g0;
    int g1;
    int g2;
    int g3;

    // variable for codemaker's response
    // red: correct color and correct position
    // white: correct color but wrong position
    // red overrides white
    int redpin;
    int whitepin;

    //you may declare additional variables here  to help you solve the problem:
    
    int attemptNumber = 1 ;  






    
    bool debug = true;

    cout << "==============================" << endl;
    cout << "Welcome to the Mastermind Game" << endl;
    cout << "==============================" << endl;

    if (debug){
        cout << "Coder maker's colors:" << endl;
        cout << "p0=" << p0 << "\tp1=" << p1 << "\tp2=" << p2 << "\tp3=" << p3 << endl << endl;
    }

    cout << "Code maker has made his choice." << endl;
    cout << "Code breaker, you have 12 attempts to crack his code." << endl;
    cout << "Game starts!" << endl << endl;

    
    // Write your code below this section:
    do {
    cout << "Attempt " << attemptNumber << endl; 
    cout <<"Please input your guess for the four positions: "<< endl; 
    //cout << "Position 1: ";
    cin >> g0; 
    //cout << "Position 2: ";
    cin >> g1; 
    //cout << "Position 3: ";
    cin >> g2; 
   // cout << "Position 4: ";
    cin >> g3; 

    redpin = 0; 
    whitepin = 0; 
    //Calculating red pins; 
    if(p0 == g0){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p1 == g1){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p2 == g2){
        redpin += 1;
    }
    if(p3 == g3){
        redpin += 1;
    }


    if (g0 == p1 || g0 == p2 || g0 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1;
    }
    if (g0 == g1 && g1 == p1){ 
        --whitepin; 
    } 
    if (g0 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
        --whitepin; 
    } 
    if (g0 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
        --whitepin; 
    }     



    if (g1 == p0 || g1 == p2 || g1 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1;
    }
    if (g1 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
    --whitepin; 
    }
    if (g1 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
    --whitepin; 
    }
    if (g1 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 






    if (g2 == p0 || g2 == p1 || g2 == p3){
        whitepin+= 1; 
    }
    if (g2 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
    --whitepin; 
    }
    if (g2 == g1 && g1== p1){ 
    --whitepin; 
    }
    if (g2 == g3 && g3 == p3){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 
    



    
    

    if (g3 == p0 || g3 == p1 || g3 == p2){
        whitepin+= 1;
    }
    if (g3 == g0 && g0 == p0){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 
    if (g3 == g1 && g1 == p1){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 
    if (g3 == g2 && g2 == p2){ 
    --whitepin; 
    } 


    if (whitepin < 0){
        whitepin = 0; 
    }

    cout<< "Red pins: " << redpin << "     White pins: " << whitepin << endl;  
    if (redpin == 4){
        cout << "Congratulations!" << endl;
        cout << "Code maker's colors: " << endl; 
        cout << "p0=" << p0 << "     p1=" <<p1 << "     p2=" << p2 << "     p3="<< p3 << endl; 
        cout << "You cracked the code with " << attemptNumber << " attempt(s)" ; 
        break; 
    }

    attemptNumber += 1;



    } while (attemptNumber < 13); 







    // Player runs out of attempts and loses 
    if (attemptNumber > 12){
    cout << "Sorry, you ran out of turns :( "<< endl; 
    }

    return 0;
}

31/03/2022, 12:55 - Tara: # put your code here

n_petals = data.groupby('Class')['Petal length'].count()
petal_prob = n_petals / len(data)

prob_set = petal_prob['Iris-setosa']
prob_vir = petal_prob['Iris-virginica']

gx = f_x_setosa * prob_set + f_x_virginica * prob_vir

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(x, gx, '-o', label = "g_x(x)")
data['Petal length'].plot.hist(bins = b, density = True)

ax.set_xlabel('Petal Lengths')
ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

13/05/2022, 23:29 - Sandeepti Singh: What are the nominee‚Äôs major contributions to the School?¬†

Through the peer mentorship programme, I had the opportunity to connect with year 1 students and guide them through any hardships they faced as new students in this university. I attempted to arrange in person meeting for my mentees whenever it was possible and safe since I felt it was easier to have a conversation with mentees in person allowing for a more personal and engaging conversation with the mentees, me to assess the specific struggles that they were more comfortable sharing in person. Mentees on zoom often had their cameras off, making it difficult to initiate a more impact and personalised conversation. I also believe that peer mentoring is not a temporary responsibility and made my number available to mentees that required frequency help and have even formed a friendship with a few of them. 

For Student Ambassador, I promoted HKUST in you high school, sharing my personal account of the opportunities and valuable experiences I have garnered in this university. For Engineering Student Ambassador, I have participated in the activities hosted for social media promotion to generate publicity for SENG. 

- How would the hall offer, if any, facilitate nominee‚Äôs service to the School?

Most of my activities and contributions to HKUST are related to giving insight based on my personal experiences. One of the biggest source of concern for mentees is to do with campus accommodation, especially international students who are drawn to me as a mentor due to similar high school experiences. Incoming students who are considering HKUST as an option share this concern and frequently inquire about hall life as it is an essential part of University life for most. However, my ability to help these students is severely limited by my lack of experiences. Due to never living on campus for a long period of time, I find myself unequipped to thoroughly address these concerns. I believe if I get a hall offer, I will be able to gain insightful experience that can in turn help mentees and potential incoming students. 

Also, the commute to and from HKUST has made it difficult to take part in a lot of on-campus activities, preventing me from interacting with more diverse people and fully immersing myself in university life. Being on campus will allow me to learn about and commit myself to new projects and organisations where I can make an impact.

24/05/2022, 11:08 - Tara: Protocol stack
1. Application: supporting network applications ‚Ä¢ HTTP, SMTP, FTP, DNS
Client-server architecture
server:
- always-on host
- permanent IP address
- server farms for scaling
clients:
- communicate with server
- may be intermittently connected
- may have dynamic IP addresses
- do not communicate directly with each other

Pure P2P architecture
- no always-on server
- arbitrary end systems directly communicate
- peers are intermittently connected and change IP addresses

Servers
- SMTP simple mail transfer protocol. Electronic mail delivery protocol
- Telnet Terminal emulation. Enables login and interactive session on a remote system
- FTP File transfer protocol. Reliable file transfer. Allows ASCII and binary files to be transferred interactively
- DNS Domain Name system. Name service used by the Internet. Can use both TCP and UDP transport-layer protocols
- HTTP 

Web and HTTP
- Web page consists of objects
- Object can be HTML file, JPEG image, Java applet, audio file
- Web page consists of base HTML-file which includes several referenced objects
- Each object is addressable by a URL

HTTP
- Web‚Äôs application layer protocol over TCP
Client/server model
- client: browser that requests, receives, ‚Äúdisplays‚Äù Web objects
- server: Web server sends objects in response to requests

Web caches: satisfy client request without involving origin server.

DNS: Domain Name System
- An Internet-wide service that provides mappings between IP addresses and hostnames
- distributed database that resides in multiple machines in the Internet, implemented in hierarchy of many name servers
- application-layer protocol host, routers, name servers to communicate to resolve names (address/name translation)
- note: an essential Internet function, implemented as application-layer protocol - usually involves short messages, and so primarily uses services provided by UDP

Local name servers
- each ISP, company has local (default) name server
- host DNS query first goes to local name server
Authoritative name server
- every host is registered with at least two authoritative servers which store that host‚Äôs IP address, name
- Can perform name/address translation for that host
Root name servers
- contacted by local name server that cannot resolve name
1. contacts authoritative name server if name mapping not known
2. gets mapping
3. returns mapping to local name server

Once (any) name server learns mapping, it caches mapping
- cache entries timeout (disappear) after some time
- TLD servers typically cached in local name servers
- Thus root name servers not often visited


2. Transport: process-process data transfer ‚Ä¢ TCP, UDP
Provide logical communication between app processes running on different hosts
Transport protocols run in end systems 
‚Äì send side: breaks app messages into segments, passes to network layer
‚Äì rcv side: reassembles segments into messages, passes to app layer

Internet: TCP and UDP
TCP: reliable, in-order
‚Äì congestion control 
‚Äì flow control
‚Äì connection setup
UDP: unreliable, unordered
‚Äì no-frills extension of ‚Äúbesteffort‚Äù IP

Functions
- Multiplexing / demultiplexing		TCP, UDP
- Error detection			TCP, UDP
- Reliable data transfer		TCP
- Flow control				TCP
- Congestion control			TCP
- Connection management			TCP

TCP reliable data transfer
Sender
- Each segment contains sequence number
- Sent segments saved in buffer
- When acknowledgement (ACK) received from  destination, remove segment from buffer
- Retransmit segment if ACK not received after ‚Äúa while.‚Äù
Receiver
- Send ACK to sender for each received packet. Indicate sequence number.
- Deliver segments to application according to sequence number

Throughput
No losses: 1/T = 1/RTT
Losses: T = (1-L)*RTT + L*(RTO+RTT)
	  = RTT + [L/(1-L)]*RTO
Best case: T = RTT/(1-L)




3. Network: routing of datagrams from source to destination ‚Ä¢ IP, routing protocols
- Packets forwarded using destination host address.
- IP: network layer of internet

Functions
- Routing: determine route taken by packets from source to destination.
- Forwarding: move packets from router's input to appropriate router output.

IP address: 32-bit long (4 bytes) identifier for host, router, interface.
Interface: connection between host/router and physical link.
IPv4 (32-bit long), max of 2^32 addresses.

Subnet: device interfaces with the same subnet part of IP address, can physically reach each other without intervening router.
CIDR: Classless InterDomain Routing
a.b.c.d/x, x = no. bits in subnet portion of address.

DHCP: Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol
Goal: allow host to dynamically obtain its IP address from network server when it joins the network.
1. host broadcasts ‚ÄúDHCP discover‚Äù msg
2. DHCP server responds with ‚ÄúDHCP offer‚Äù msg
3. host requests IP address: ‚ÄúDHCP request‚Äù msg
4. DHCP server sends address: ‚ÄúDHCP ack‚Äù msg

IPv6: fixed-length 40 byte header, max of 2^128 addresses.




4. Link: data transfer between neighboring network elements ‚Ä¢ 802.11, Ethernet
Data-link layer: transferring datagram from one node to adjacent node over a link.
Data transmitted in units of frames (groups of bits)
Services
- Framing, link access - encapsulates datagram into frame, adding header, trailer.
- Error detection - signals sende for retransmission / drops frames.
- Error correction: receiver identifies and corrects bit errors without retransmitting.
Sending side						Receiving side
- Encapsulates datagram in frame.			- Looks for errors
- Adds error checking bits and other headers.		- Extracts datagram, passes to upper layer
Two types of links: point to point (PPP) and broadcast (sared wire / medium)
Multiple Access Protocol							Ideal
- Distributed algorithm that determines how nodes share channel.		When M nodes want to transmit at rate R, average rate = R/M
- Communication about channel sharing must use channel itself.			Simple
										Fully decentralised
Media Access Control (MAC) Protocols
- Channel partitioning: divide channel into smaller pieces.
- Random access: channel not divided, allows collisions.
- Taking turns: nodes take turns, but nodes with more to send can take longer turns.

Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA)				Frequency Division Multiple Access (FDMA)
- Access to channel in rounds.					- Channel spectrum divided into frequency bands.
- Each station gets fixed-length slot in each round.		- Each station assigned fixed frequency band.
- Unused slots go idle.						- Unused transmission time in frequency bands go idle.

Random access protocols
- How to detect collisions.
- How to recover from collisions.
e.g. slotted ALOHA, pure ALOHA, CSMA, CSMA/CD, CSMA/CA

Slotted ALOHA
- Time divided into slots equal to length of one packet.
- Packets transmitted starting only at the start of each slot.
- If collision, both packets lost
Pros										Cons
- Single active node can continuously transmit at full rate of channel.		- Collisions, wasting slots
- Highly decentralised.								- Idle slots
- Simple									- Once collision occurs, entire slot is wasted.
										- Clock synchronisation
Effiency: fraction of time slots w/ successful transmission.
Throughput: number of packets transmitted per time interval.
Assumptions
- Nodes operate independently
- Each node has a queue to hold packets.
- If the queue is non-empty, the node is backlogged.
- Backlogged nodes send packets in each timeslot with probability p
- Assume N nodes are backlogged.
N nodes, probability of transmission p
No node transmits in slot: (1-p)^N
Partiular node transmits w/o collision: N * p * (1-p)^(N-1)
Probability of collision: 1 - [N * p^1 * (1-p)^(N-1)]
Efficiency: N * p * (1-p)^(N-1)
Max efficiency: p=1/N




5. Physical: bits ‚Äúon the wire‚Äù
